<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<worksheet>
  <title>BF-4 Sample Outcomes</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      This outcome covers transformations and combinations of functions. You will be asked to identify basic 
      functions, and the transformations applied to them. You will be asked to use transformations in the 
      correct order to find new points or graphs. Given two functions, you will be asked to evaluate the 
      combinations or the combination at a point. Given two functions, you should be able to evaluate their 
      composition or the composition at a point. You should be able to write out complete steps to solve these 
      types of problems by hand, without the use of a calculator.
    </p>
    <p>For the quiz on this outcome you would be given 30 minutes to complete 2 problems. Here are samples 
      of the types of problems you will encounter:</p>
  </introduction>
  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Simplifying Expressions: Simplify algebraic expressions by combining like terms and applying the 
        distributive property. Answers should be completely simplified.</p></li>
      <li><p>Problem structure: Solution should be organized and easy to follow, with clear, complete steps 
        that follow progressively from one to the next.</p></li>
      <li><p>Mathematical Communication: Solutions should be presented in a clear and logical manner, with 
        appropriate use of mathematical notation and terminology. Equations should have at most one equal 
        sign and expressions on both sides.</p></li>
      <li><p>Transformations: Given a function <m>f(x)</m>, identify and apply various transformations to 
        translate points or a graph.</p></li>
      <li><p>Combinations: Given two functions <m>f(x)</m> and <m>g(x)</m>, evaluate their sum, difference, 
        product, and quotient at values or expressions.</p></li>
    </ul>
    </objectives>

  
  <page>
    <exercise workspace="3cm">
      <introduction><p>
          Given the function <m>f(x)=\frac{2}{x+4}-1</m>.
      </p></introduction>
      <task>
        <statement><p>State the basic function.</p></statement>
        <solution><p><m>y=\frac{1}{x}</m></p></solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><p>State the transformations applied to the basic function.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>Look at the function <m>f(x)=\frac{2}{x+4}-1</m> and 
          compare it to the basic function <m>y=\frac{1}{x}</m>. Think 
          about what the numerical coefficients and constants represent, 
          as well as any negative signs.</p></hint>
        <solution><p>The transformations applied are: a horizontal shift 
          left by 4 units, a vertical stretch by a factor of 2, and a 
          vertical shift down by 1 unit.</p></solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><p>Determine where the point <m>(2,\frac{1}{2})</m> would be translated to 
        on <m>f</m> under the transformations.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>Use the order of transformations to move the point: horizontal shift, 
          vertical stretch, vertical shift.</p></hint>
        <answer><p><m>(-2,0)</m></p></answer>
        <solution><p>First we will apply the horizontal shift left by 4 units, which 
          moves the point from <m>(2,\frac{1}{2})</m> to <m>(-2,\frac{1}{2})</m>. Next, 
          we will apply the vertical stretch by a factor of 2, which multiplies the 
          y-coordinate by 2, resulting in <m>(-2,1)</m>. Finally, we will apply the 
          vertical shift down by 1 unit, which subtracts 1 from the y-coordinate, 
          resulting in <m>(-2,0)</m>.</p></solution>
      </task>
    </exercise>

    <exercise workspace="3cm">
      <introduction><p>
          Given the function <m>f(x)</m> shown below, find the graph of the transformed function <m>g(x)</m>.</p>
          <image width="60%">
              <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org"
                          label="prefigure-bf4a-sample">
                <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                  <coordinates bbox="(-10,-10,10,10)">
                    <grid spacings="((-10,2,10),(-10,2,10))"/>
                    <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
                    <path start="(-6,2)" stroke="blue">
                      <lineto point="(-2,3)"/>
                      <arc center="(0,3)" radius="2" range="(180,360)"/>
                      <lineto point="(4,3)"/>
                      <lineto point="(7,-1)"/>
                      </path>
                  </coordinates>
                  <annotations>
                  <annotation ref="figure"
                    text="The graph is a piecewise graph consisting of four connected segments. The first segment is a line 
                    with a positive slope starting at (-6,2) and ending at (-2,3), the second segment is the bottom 
                    of a semicircle starting at (-2,3) and ending at (2,3) with a radius of 2, the third segment is a 
                    horizontal line segment starting at (2,3) and ending at (4,3), and the fourth segment is a line 
                    with a negative slope starting at (4,3) and ending at the point (7,-1)."/>
                  </annotations>
                </diagram>
              </prefigure>
            </image>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement><p>If <m>g(x)=3-2f(x+1)</m>, state the transformations applied to <m>f(x)</m>.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>Look at the numbers and minus signs in the function for g. Think 
          about what these represent in terms of transformations.</p></hint>
        <solution><p>The transformations applied are: a horizontal shift left by 1 unit, a vertical 
          stretch by a factor of 2, a reflection about the x-axis, and a vertical shift up by 3 units.</p></solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><p>Sketch the graph of <m>g(x)</m>.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>Use the order of transformations to move the graph: horizontal shift, 
          vertical stretch, reflection, and vertical shift.</p></hint>
        <answer><image width="60%">
              <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org"
                          label="prefigure-bf4b-sample">
                <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                  <coordinates bbox="(-10,-10,10,10)">
                    <grid spacings="((-10,1,10),(-10,1,10))"/>
                    <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
                      <path start="(-7,-1)" stroke="red">
                      <lineto point="(-3,-3)"/>
                      <cubic-bezier controls="((-2,2.5),(0,2.5),(1,-3))"/>
                      <lineto point="(3,-3)"/>
                      <lineto point="(6,5)"/>
                      </path>
                  </coordinates>
                  <annotations>
                  <annotation ref="figure"
                    text="The graph is a piecewise graph consisting of four connected segments. The first segment is a line 
                    with a negative slope starting at (-7,-1) and ending at (-3,-3), the second segment is the top 
                    of a parabola starting at (-3,-3) and ending at (1,3) with a vertex at (-1,1), the third segment is a horizontal line 
                    from (1,-3) to (3,-3), and the fourth segment is a line with a positive slope ending at the point (6,5)."/>
                  </annotations>
                </diagram>
              </prefigure>
            </image></answer>
        <solution><p>First we will apply the horizontal shift left by 1 unit which subtracts 1 
          from all of the x-coordinates. Next, we will apply the vertical stretch by a factor 
          of 2, which multiplies all of the y-coordinates by 2. Then we will apply the reflection 
          about the x-axis, which multiplies all of the y-coordinates by -1. Finally, we will 
          apply the vertical shift up by 3 units, which adds 3 to all of the y-coordinates.</p></solution>
      </task>
    </exercise>

    <exercise workspace="3cm">
      <introduction><p>
        Given <m>f(x)=\frac{x}{x+1}</m> and <m>g(x)=3x^2+3</m>, find and simplify the following:
      </p></introduction>
      <task>
        <statement><p><m>(f+g)(-4)</m></p></statement>
        <hint><p>Recall that <m>(f+g)(x)=f(x)+g(x)</m></p></hint>
        <answer><p><m>(f+g)(-4)= \frac{157}{3}</m></p></answer>
        <solution><p><m>(f+g)(-4) \amp = f(-4) + g(-4)\\
          \amp = \frac{-4}{-4+1} + 3(-4)^2 + 3\\
          \amp = \frac{4}{3} + 48 + 3\\
          \amp = \frac{157}{3}\end{aligned}</m></p></solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><p><m>(f-g)(x)</m></p></statement>
        <hint><p>Recall that <m>(f-g)(x)=f(x)-g(x)</m></p></hint>
        <answer><p><m>(f-g)(x)= \frac{-3x^3-3x^2+4x+3}{x+1}</m></p></answer>
        <solution><p><m>(f-g)(x) \amp = f(x)-g(x)\\ \amp= \frac{x}{x+1}-3x^2+3\\
          \amp= \frac{x-3x^2(x+1)+3(x+1)}{x+1}\\
          \amp= \frac{-3x^3-3x^2+4x+3}{x+1}\end{aligned}</m></p></solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><p><m>\left(\frac{f}{g}\right)(3)</m></p></statement>
        <hint><p>Recall that <m>\left(\frac{f}{g}\right)(x)=\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}</m></p></hint>
        <answer><p><m>\left(\frac{f}{g}\right)(3)= \frac{1}{40}</m></p></answer>
        <solution><p><m>\left(\frac{f}{g}\right)(3) \amp = \frac{f(3)}{g(3)}\\
          \amp = \frac{\frac{3}{3+1}}{3(3)^2+3}\\
          \amp = \frac{\frac{3}{4}}{27+3}\\
          \amp = \frac{\frac{3}{4}}{30}\\
          \amp = \frac{3}{4} \cdot \frac{1}{30}\\
          \amp = \frac{1}{40}\end{aligned}</m></p></solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><p><m>(f\circ g)(x)</m></p></statement>
        <hint><p>Recall that <m>(f\circ g)(x)=f(g(x))</m></p></hint>
        <answer><p><m>(f\circ g)(x) =\frac{3x^2+3}{3x^2+4}\end{aligned}</m></p></answer>
        <solution><p><m>(f\circ g)(x) \amp = f(g(x))\\ \amp= f(3x^2+3)\\
          \amp= \frac{3x^2+3}{3x^2+3+1}\\
          \amp= \frac{3x^2+3}{3x^2+4}\end{aligned}</m></p></solution>
      </task>
    </exercise>
  </page>
</worksheet> 
